US Flight Delay and Cancellation Trends in 2019¶

by Dagmara Namasivayam¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

This dataset reports flights in the United States, including arrival and departure delays, cancellations, and reasons for delays and cancellations, for the whole year of 2019.

I wanted to gather more years' worth of data, but each month of data was so large that I had to limit how many months I gathered. I was interested in trends across seasons, so I wanted to have all months for at least one year. I felt that to be fair, if I included another year, I should include as many months as the first year, which would have made my dataset way too slow to process on my computer. So, even though I started off by including years other than 2019, I decided to just explore the most recent year's data.

I'm trying to figure out when there is no reason given for the delay. It seems that it's always given if the arrival delay is at least 15 minutes. On the other hand, length of departure delays doesn't seem to affect whether there are nulls.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

My dataset has 7434871 datapoints each representing a flight in 2019. There are 19 variables (after deleting ones that are not of interest) describing each flight, however there are many null values for causes of delay (last 5 columns). Departure/arrival times/delays also have some null values, as well as many in the cancellations column. Some of these nulls just indicate that a flight was cancelled/never departed. In general, most variables are numeric, but cancellation code and carrier code are strings.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm interested in learning what variables are correlated with delays and cancellations. I'm also interested in the reasons for cancellations and for delays.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I think certain airports may experience more delays than others, maybe even certain origin-desitination pairs. I think scheduled time of flight, and possibly day of the week, will also contribute.

Univariate Exploration¶

I'll start by looking at the distribution of the first main variable of interest, which is delay. Let's look at both departure and arrival delay, but I'll probably mostly consider just arrival delay, since that's what seems to matter more, and the two are often related.

Plotting arrival delay on a log scale is not so helpful, since we can't plot negative delays (early arrivals). However, we can see the values a little better now. Depending on the bin size, we get a small spike somewhere between 10 and 100 min, but in general, the delay count falls off quite rapidly with increasing delay.

Perhaps a better visual is still the normal scale, but displayed with only the top 95% of the data.

It turns out that the arrival delay distribution is unimodal and heavily right skewed, with the peak delay actually just below 0 at 10 minutes early.

Since the arrival delay distribution is not so easy to deal with, let's look at adding a variable for simply "delayed" or "not delayed", and also one for breaking the delay into descrete bins.

In [34]:
# Consider cancelled flights "delayed"
flights2019['DELAYED'] = (flights2019.ARR_DELAY>0) | (flights2019.CANCELLED==1)

# upto_1hr = ((flights2019.ARR_DELAY>5) & (flights2019.ARR_DELAY<=60))
upto_1hr = ((flights2019.ARR_DELAY>0) & (flights2019.ARR_DELAY<=60))
over_1hr = (flights2019.ARR_DELAY>60)
cancelled = flights2019.CANCELLED==1

flights2019.loc[ontime,'DELAY_BIN'] = 'on time'
# flights2019.loc[upto_5min,'DELAY_BIN'] = '5 min late'
flights2019.loc[upto_1hr,'DELAY_BIN'] = '1 hour late'
flights2019.loc[over_1hr,'DELAY_BIN'] = 'over 1 hour late'
flights2019.loc[cancelled,'DELAY_BIN'] = 'cancelled'

I considered breaking the delay into various different bins, thinking that +/- 5 min didn't mean anything, or that maybe we're interested if a flight is not just on-time, but early. Ultimately though, I chose this simple breakdown that nobody can argue with.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The arrival delay distribution is unimodal and heavily right skewed, with the peak delay actually just below 0 at 10 minutes EARLY. With the long tail at higher values, I initially performed a log transformation to plot. This didn't give me any new insights, so I went back to the original plot, but visualized with the top 95% of delay values. I also made another column corresponding to delay bins, which was easier to visualize. That plot was distributed as expected.

The cancellation plot was a boring one, but it also looked at expected, with only a small percentage of total flight cancellations in 2019.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

None of the distributions seemed unusual to me, except the flight count over seasons, which upon further inspection seems valid. The basic shapes of the other variables were expected based on what I understand about US flights.

Besides making the new column for a categorical version of departure delay, I had to make a new variable for season to plot the count plot of flights by season. I also had to adjust the scheduled departure time variable so I could plot it as a histogram properly, making it categorical by extracting the hour. I also added an additional column corresponding to whether the scheduled departure time was in the morning or afternoon, so I could easier compare just those 2 categories. For exploring cancellations and cancellation causes, I chose to plot those as proportions instead of just counts so that they could be compared easier.

These results are interesting, because I expected the airports in cities with colder seasons to have delays due to snowstorms. This hypothesis is consistent with results from LAX, but not the others. One possible explanation is that all airports can be affected by snowstorms in only certain cities. For example, since Atlanta is a big airline hub, it's greatly affected by weather in colder cities. Another explanation is that of course 'weather' doesn't have to mean snowstorms. Hurricanes, although much less common, would also severely disrupt flights in large regions, as would thunderstorms/hail. Still, LAX is different from all these other airports in that weather is never the main cause of delay, no matter which season. At ORD, DFW, and DEN, weather is the leading cause of cancellation for all seasons. Additionally, the only times that cancellations due to NAS were more common than carrier cancellations were at ORD in summer and winter, as well as DFW in the fall. Lastly, cancellations due to security are an insigificant percentage of cancellations across the board.
